[
    {
        "content": "<p>Here is my amateurish definition of a groupoid: a groupoid is a category <code>G</code> for which there is a functor <code>inv : G -&gt; G^op</code> that is the identity on objects, such that for any morphism <code>p : G(A, B)</code>, <code>inv(p) . p = idA</code> and <code>p . inv(p) = idB</code></p>\n<p>Now I don't want to say things like \"functor that is the identity on objects\" and so on, but I'm not sure how to avoid it. Is there a way I can characterize a groupoid as an object in Cat that is equipped with some additional 1,2-cells and equations?</p>",
        "id": 234715112,
        "sender_full_name": "Asad Saeeduddin",
        "timestamp": 1618506222
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is a sort of famous problem, that becomes more serious for dagger categories: a generalization of groupoids where you have a functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>†</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\dagger</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">†</span></span></span></span> that's the identity on objects, for which <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>†</mo><mo>∘</mo><mo>†</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\dagger \\circ \\dagger</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">†</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∘</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">†</span></span></span></span> is the identity.   People worry about whether saying \"the identity on objects\" is evil:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/220032/are-dagger-categories-truly-evil\">Are dagger categories truly evil</a>, <em>MathOverflow</em>.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/principle+of+equivalence#daggers\">Principle of equivalence - for dagger-categories</a>, nLab.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So, I think reading the whole discussions there would be good.</p>",
        "id": 234721954,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1618508706
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By the way, if you really want to avoid saying \"functor that is the identity on objects\", how do you plan to define the identity functor?</p>",
        "id": 234722696,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1618508994
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275920\">@John Baez</span> i'd say it's the neutral element of functor composition (i.e. it is the identity endomorphism of each object in Cat)</p>",
        "id": 234725618,
        "sender_full_name": "Asad Saeeduddin",
        "timestamp": 1618510146
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>i hope that somehow avoids talking about the objects of the category itself and the \"action\" of the functor on them. but maybe that isn't really accomplishing anything beyond talking about objects directly, i'm not sure</p>",
        "id": 234725666,
        "sender_full_name": "Asad Saeeduddin",
        "timestamp": 1618510163
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/How.20to.20characterize.20a.20groupoid.20by.20its.20equipment.20in.20Cat/near/234722696\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>By the way, if you really want to avoid saying \"functor that is the identity on objects\", how do you plan to define the identity functor?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That's a different question -- when we define <em>the</em> identity functor we can define it to act by <em>the</em> identity function on objects.  It doesn't require referring to an equality <em>relation</em> between two given objects, which is what one needs to say, as a <em>property</em> of a hypothesized functor, that it acts as the identity on objects.</p>",
        "id": 234739360,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1618515406
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276050\">Asad Saeeduddin</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/How.20to.20characterize.20a.20groupoid.20by.20its.20equipment.20in.20Cat/near/234715112\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Is there a way I can characterize a groupoid as an object in Cat that is equipped with some additional 1,2-cells and equations?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>A groupoid is an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mo>∈</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G\\in \\rm Cat</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.72243em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">t</span></span></span></span></span> together with, for every pair of 1-cells <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>→</mo><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x,y:1\\to G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> and 2-cell <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>⇒</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha : x\\Rightarrow y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⇒</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span></span></span></span>, a 2-cell <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>β</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>⇒</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\beta:y\\Rightarrow x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">β</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⇒</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi><mi>β</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha\\beta = 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">β</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>β</mi><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\beta\\alpha=1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05278em;\">β</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>If you don't like giving a special role to the terminal category 1 (e.g. if you want to generalize to other 2-categories), you can assert the same condition for 1-cells <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x,y:X\\to G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> for an arbitrary object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>.  This works just as well in Cat, and in any 2-category gives the correct notion of <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/truncated+object\">groupoidal object</a>.</p>\n<p>If you don't like quantifying over all objects <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> of the category, you can say that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> is a groupoid if the map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mo>→</mo><msup><mi>G</mi><mn mathvariant=\"bold\">2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G \\to G^{\\mathbf{2}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbf mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is an equivalence, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn mathvariant=\"bold\">2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">2</span></span></span></span></span> is the interval category.  This works in any 2-category that admits powers by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn mathvariant=\"bold\">2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">2</span></span></span></span></span>, and gives the same notion of groupoidal object.</p>",
        "id": 234740210,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1618515736
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Could you get the same from demanding that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> satisfies the universal property for the power by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn mathvariant=\"bold\">2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">2</span></span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 234780478,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1618536405
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah.  But that gets you back to quantifying over all objects of the category, whereas if there already are powers then you can consider them a finitary operation.  (-:</p>",
        "id": 234788901,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1618544231
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276777\">@Mike Shulman</span> beautiful, thanks very much</p>",
